'''Scott Ethan Allen''' (born February 8, 1949 in [[Newark, New Jersey]]) is an [[United States|American]] [[Figure skating|figure skater]]. He is the [[Figure skating at the 1964 Winter Olympics|1964 Olympic bronze medalist]], the 1965 [[World Figure Skating Championships|World silver medalist]], and the 1964 and 1966 [[United States Figure Skating Championships|U.S. national champion]].
Allen made his national debut at the age of 9, winning the silver medal in the novice men's division at the 1959 U.S. Championships. At that time he was the youngest competitor ever to skate in the Championships.<ref>"The United States Championships", ''Skating'' magazine, March 1959</ref>
He won the bronze medal at the [[1964 Winter Olympics]] two days before his 15th birthday, becoming the youngest medalist at the Winter Olympics.<ref>[http://www.iviesinathens.com/olympic/games.aspx?ID=209 Ivy League Sports - Ivies in Athens 2004<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He still holds the record for the youngest male medalist and the youngest individual medalist.<ref>[http://multimedia.olympic.org/pdf/en_report_847.pdf Facsheet<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
He represented the [[Skating Club of New York]] in competition.<ref>{{PDFlink|[http://www.xcelenergycenter.com/uploads/assets/saintpaul2008/news/Past%20U.S.%20Champions.pdf Past U.S. Champions - Senior]|123&nbsp;[[Kibibyte|KiB]]<!-- application/pdf, 126512 bytes -->}}</ref> After his skating career, Allen attended [[Harvard University]], class of 1971. He currently{{When|date=September 2009}} resides in Tenafly, NJ{{Citation needed|date=September 2009}}.
